06349nam a22006855i 9780228004530DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212021xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280045307 a10.1515/97802280045302doi  a(DE-B1597)656870  a(OCoLC)1243321124  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aLIT0190002bisacsh04a820.9/353qOCoLC223/eng/2023021600aOvid and Masculinity in English Renaissance Literature /ced. by Goran Stanivukovic, John S. Garrison. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource :b3 photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tOvid and Masculinity in English Renaissance Literature -- tAuthority and Embodiment -- tOvid's Orpheus and the Soft Masculinity of English Poetics -- tAbject Authorship: A Portrait of the Artist in Ovid and His Renaissance Imitators -- tOvid in Love and War: Pacifist Masculinity in Shakespeare's Venus and Adonis -- tThe Faerie Queene's Muses: “Hermaphrodites,„ Masculine Education, and Inspiration -- tSexuality and Desire -- tThe Birth of Tragedy: Milton, Ovidian Masculinity, and Poliziano's Orfeo -- tOvid and Unheroic Masculinity in the Prose Romance of the English Renaissance -- tAfter Ovid's Sappho: Muteness Envy, Female Masculinity, and the Ethics of Mutability -- tMaturation of Youth -- t“Of Youth and Age„: Ovid and Generational Masculinities in Ben Jonson's Poetaster (1602) -- tMaking a Politic Gentleman: The First Ars amatoria in English -- tBoys to Men: Fashioning Masculinity and Parody in the Ovidian Epyllia -- tThe Body and Religion -- tThe Uncooked Goose: Ovid's Philemon, Milton's Adam, and the Transformation of Hospitable Manliness -- tOvid's Proteus and the Figure of the Male Jew in Marlowe's The Jew of Malta -- tEnvoy -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOvid transformed English Renaissance literary ideas about love, erotic desire, embodiment, and gender more than any other classical poet. Ovidian concepts of femininity have been well served by modern criticism, but Ovid's impact on masculinity in Renaissance literature remains underexamined. This volume explores how English Renaissance writers shifted away from Virgilian heroic figures to embrace romantic ideals of courtship, civility, and friendship. Ovid's writing about masculinity, love, and desire shaped discourses of masculinity across a wide range of literary texts of the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries, including poetry, prose fiction, and drama. The book covers all major works by Ovid, in addition to Italian humanists Angelo Poliziano and Natale Conti, canonical writers such as William Shakespeare, Christopher Marlowe, Ben Jonson, Edmund Spenser, Philip Sidney, and John Milton, and lesser-known writers such as Wynkyn de Worde, Michael Drayton, Thomas Lodge, Richard Johnson, Robert Greene, John Marston, Thomas Heywood, and Francis Beaumont. Individual essays examine emasculation, abjection, pacifism, female masculinity, boys' masculinity, parody, hospitality, and protean Jewish masculinity. Ovid and Masculinity in English Renaissance Literature demonstrates how Ovid's poetry gave vigour and vitality to male voices in English literature - how his works inspired English writers to reimagine the male authorial voice, the male body, desire, and love in fresh terms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aMasculinity in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Renaissance.2bisacsh1 aBates, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarter, Sarah, econtributor